s":"Wales","Aberedw, Sir Powys, Wales, United Kingdom":"Aberedw, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","Not known":"Not, Graz Umgebung, Styria, Austria","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales","Aber Garth Celyn, Gwynedd, Wales":"Aber, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["German: occupational name for a ferryman, Middle High German <i>verje</i>, <i>verge</i>."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Abt  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name from Apt, the Yiddish name of Opatów in Świętokrzyskie Voivodeship, Poland. The placename (in German, Yiddish, and Polish) is from a root meaning ‘abbot’, the place having been named for the local abbey. Compare   Abt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Griffith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffieth","meanings":["Variant of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griff","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone living near a pit or hollow, from Middle English <i>grif</i> ‘pit, hollow, narrow valley’ (Old Norse <i>gryfja</i>), or a habitational name from Griff in Warwickshire, Griffe in Derbyshire, or Griff Farm in Rievaulx, North Yorkshire, all probably named with this word.","Welsh and English: from the Welsh personal name <i>Gryff</i>, a short form of <i>Gruffudd</i>. See   Griffith  .","German: variant of   Greif   1."]},{"name":"Kerfoot","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire):","habitational name, probably from Carefoot, near Myerscough (Lancashire).","possibly a variant of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffes","meanings":["Welsh: altered form of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffeth","meanings":["Altered form of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffiths","meanings":["Welsh (Glamorgan and western England): Anglicized form of the patronymic <i>(ap) Gruffudd</i>, from Old Welsh <i>Grippiud</i> (see   Griffith  )."]},{"name":"Griffth","meanings":["Variant of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffitt","meanings":["Altered form of   Griffith  ."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Variant of   Katherine ."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Catherine ferch Llywelyn Ap Griffith was born in 1279, in Wales, her father, Llywelyn ap Gruffydd Prince of North Wales, was 56 and her mother, Eleanor de Montfort, was 27. She married Philip ab Ifor Lord of Iscoed in 1296. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1340, in Cardiganshire, Wales, at the age of 61, and was buried in Not, Graz Umgebung, Styria, Austria."},"et":{"1279–1340":"1279–1340","1282–1337":"1282–1337","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1305–1337":"1305–1337","1223–1282":"1223–1282","1252–1282":"1252–1282","1305":"1305","13 October 1278":"13. oktoober 1278","1337":"1337","1279":"1279","122